  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Ascending Shaoyang Pavilion
  author: Kim Si-seup
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Beyond the birds, heaven begins to fade.
    Alongside my sorrow, regret knows no rest.
    Mountains curve, rolling down from the north,
    While the river flows of its own toward the west.
    Geese descend where sandbars stretch far,
    And the boat returns to ancient banks, hushed and deep.
    When shall I cast off the world's tangled net?
    Riding this mood, I would come here again to wander.
  footnotes:
    - Shaoyang Pavilion (昭陽亭) was a famous pavilion in ancient China associated with contemplation and melancholy.
    - The imagery of geese, rivers, and ancient banks reflects common motifs in East Asian poetry symbolizing transience and nostalgia.
    - The final couplet expresses the poet's desire to transcend worldly concerns and return to this place of natural beauty and spiritual solace.
